<a href="javascript:card_browser(144)">Morgul Hunter</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(147)">Morgul Warden</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(149)">Orc Assassin</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(154)">Orc Inquisitor</a> x3<br>
Orc Pillager x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(998)">Tower Assassin</a> x2<br>
Ulaire Enquea x2<br>
Ulaire Toldea<br>
<br>
Conditions (6):<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(135)">Desperate Defense of the Ring</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(163)">Thin and Stretched</a> x2<br>
<br>
Events (7):<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(867)">Enduring Evil</a> x4<br>
Gleaming In The Snow x3<br>
<br>
<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> The fellowship side is pretty standard Trust Me, I guess. Start Aragorn if you go second and site 1 isn&#39;t Pony, otherwise start Gandalf. Play everything as you draw it, except for companions; obviously stay under 6 (or under 5 against Uruks). Feel free to kill off less important companions like Legolas to make room for more important guys like Gimli. If you think you might need guys like Filibert and Thrarin at sites 7-9, you might want to save them and play them after site 7, or make sure you beat your opponent there so their site gets played and maybe it won&#39;t discard them (this deck plays site 7 discard allies because if your opponent beats you to site 7 your shadow is going to need all the help it can get.)<br>
<br>
The shadow is where the deck really shines, though. I rarely get a minion win, but the minions intimidate the opponent from double moving, which is all a shadow side really needs to do anyway. The important thing is to play all your conditions ASAP, even if it means that at *this* site, the one orc you played and exerted twice will die to archery; the point is that at the next site you&#39;ll be adding more burdens. Hold Enduring Evils until they&#39;ll make a difference; don&#39;t pitch any just to get them out of your hand, unless you&#39;ve also holding onto at least 2. Also hold onto Gleaming in the Snow until you can play it, unless they aren&#39;t playing any Gondor companions for some reason.<br>
<br>
Remember that the real point of your shadow side isn&#39;t to win, it&#39;s to slow down your opponent while your fellowship runs as fast as it can. Nothing runs like Trust Me, anyway. Always remember that you&#39;ve only got to just barely survive that last dash to 9. I once fought off 3 Troops Of Uruk-Hai, an Uruk Captain, an Uruk Ravager, and Saruman at site 9 without Filibert&#39;s help with this deck. As long as you&#39;ve got a Trust Me or two out and a Servant or two in your hand, don&#39;t be askeered of anything.<br>
